>are</strong> in the scheme, you’ll only pay tax on rental income you get over £4,250. </p>\n\n<p>Rental income includes money you get for extra services you provide, like meals and laundry. You won’t be able to claim any expenses.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The £4,250 allowance may be halved if someone else in the property - like your partner - also receives income from letting.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>How to get the allowance</h2>\n<p>You’ll get the tax exemption automatically if both of the following apply:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you don’t normally receive a tax return</li>\n  <li>the yearly amount you get in rent, plus income from extra services you provide, is £4,250 or less</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you get more than £4,250, you should complete a <a href=\"/self-assessment-tax-returns/overview\" title=\"Self Assessment tax returns\">tax return</a>. You opt into the Rent a Room scheme on the Self Assessment form.</p>\n\n<p>If you want to opt out, complete a tax return and declare the relevant lettings income and expenses on the property pages.</p>\n\n<p>Read the Rent a Room helpsheet for more detailed information on how to complete the form, and when it makes sense to opt out of the scheme.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/helpsheets/hs223.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Helpsheet 223: Rent a Room for traders' (PDF, 77KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Helpsheet 223: Rent a Room for traders’ (PDF, 77KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Eligibility</h2>\n<p>You can opt in to the scheme at any time if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you’re a resident landlord, whether or not you own your home</li>\n  <li>you run a bed and breakfast or a guest house</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can’t use the scheme for homes converted into separate flats.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/rent-room-in-your-home/your-lodgers-tenancy-type","slug":"your-lodgers-tenancy-type","order":3,"title":"Your lodger's tenancy type","body":"<p>The way you share your home with a lodger affects what kind of tenancy they have. This in turn affects their rights and how you can end the tenancy. </p>\n\n<h2>Your lodger is an excluded occupier</h2>\n\n<p>Your lodger is likely to be an excluded occupier if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>they live in your home</li>\n  <li>you or a member of your family share a kitchen, bathroom or living room with them</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In this case, you only have to give them reasonable notice to <a href=\"/rent-room-in-your-home/ending-a-letting\" title=\"Ending a letting\">end the letting</a> - and you won&rsquo;t have to go to court to evict them.</p>\n\n<h2>Your lodger has basic protection</h2>\n\n<p>Your lodger is likely to be an occupier with basic protection if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>they live in your home</li>\n  <li>they don&rsquo;t share any living space with you or your family</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If your lodger won&rsquo;t leave when you ask them, you&rsquo;ll need to get a court order to <a href=\"/rent-room-in-your-home/ending-a-letting\" title=\"Ending a letting\">evict them</a>. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The charity Shelter has advice on <a href=\"http://england.shelter.org.uk/get_advice/renting_and_leasehold/private_tenancies/excluded_occupiers\" title=\"Excluded tenancies: Shelter\" rel=\"external\">excluded occupiers</a> and <a href=\"http://england.shelter.org.uk/get_advice/renting_and_leasehold/private_tenancies/occupiers_with_basic_protection\" title=\"Non-excluded tenancies\" rel=\"external\">occupiers with basic protection.</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>The length of the let</h2>\n<p>A tenancy or a licence can be either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>periodic - run indefinitely from one rent period to the next</li>\n  <li>fixed term - last a set number of weeks, months or years</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you don’t agree the length of a let, it will automatically become a periodic let. </p>\n\n<p>Licences can be open-ended for informal arrangements, like allowing a friend to stay on an as-a